WEBVTT

1
00:00:04.726 --> 00:00:06.511
[Noah] Previously on The Affair...

2
00:00:06.512 --> 00:00:08.511
Author of the best-selling
novel. Descent.

3
00:00:08.512 --> 00:00:11.135
soon to be made into a
major motion picture.

4
00:00:11.136 --> 00:00:12.761
Noah Solloway.

5
00:00:12.762 --> 00:00:14.761
People know my movies. and
they see me as this. um.

6
00:00:14.762 --> 00:00:16.511
you know. this action hero.

7
00:00:16.512 --> 00:00:18.506
this sort of modern-day James Bond.

8
00:00:18.507 --> 00:00:19.719
But that's all an act. of course.

9
00:00:19.720 --> 00:00:21.665
I mean. that's not who I am.

10
00:00:21.666 --> 00:00:23.653
But this book. this is me.

11
00:00:23.654 --> 00:00:26.153
So what's your plan to make money?

12
00:00:26.154 --> 00:00:27.848
Ugh. I don't know.

13
00:00:27.849 --> 00:00:31.081
His visa's about to expire.
so no one will hire him.

14
00:00:31.082 --> 00:00:33.464
I just wanted to say I
think it's so awesome

15
00:00:33.465 --> 00:00:35.105
that you're my dad's girlfriend.

16
00:00:36.293 --> 00:00:37.511
Can I trouble you for another drink?

17
00:00:37.512 --> 00:00:40.135
[scoffs] Of course. Coming right up.

18
00:00:40.136 --> 00:00:41.886
[Noah] There's something wrong with him.

19
00:00:41.887 --> 00:00:44.037
He's losing his memory. He thinks
I'm still married to Helen.

20
00:00:44.038 --> 00:00:45.317
He thinks I own this place.

21
00:00:45.318 --> 00:00:47.220
[exhales] I need to leave.

22
00:00:49.345 --> 00:00:50.470
Come in.

23
00:00:52.220 --> 00:00:54.302
Vik. this is your son.

24
00:00:54.303 --> 00:00:56.094
This is Eddie.

25
00:00:56.095 --> 00:00:57.844
[Eddie coos softly]

26
00:00:57.845 --> 00:00:59.094
Are you with the studio?

27
00:00:59.095 --> 00:01:00.427
[scoffs] No.

28
00:01:00.428 --> 00:01:01.640
S-So you're...

29
00:01:01.641 --> 00:01:02.803
Helen.

30
00:01:02.804 --> 00:01:05.260
I lost my partner a few
months ago. [crying]

31
00:01:05.261 --> 00:01:07.052
Oh. my God.

32
00:01:07.053 --> 00:01:08.618
Just breathe.

33
00:01:08.619 --> 00:01:10.979
- I lost someone. too.
- [Paul] Where are you gonna stay?

34
00:01:10.980 --> 00:01:12.010
Dad's place.

35
00:01:12.011 --> 00:01:14.011
[Paul] Is that a good idea?

36
00:01:22.365 --> 00:01:25.522
♪ I was screaming into the canyon ♪

37
00:01:25.523 --> 00:01:28.829
♪ At the moment of my death ♪

38
00:01:28.830 --> 00:01:31.594
♪ The echo I created ♪

39
00:01:31.595 --> 00:01:35.135
♪ Outlasted my last breath ♪

40
00:01:35.136 --> 00:01:38.889
♪ My voice it made an avalanche ♪

41
00:01:38.890 --> 00:01:41.833
♪ And buried a man I never knew ♪

42
00:01:41.834 --> 00:01:44.992
♪ And when he died. his widowed bride ♪

43
00:01:44.993 --> 00:01:47.789
♪ Met your daddy and they made you ♪

44
00:01:47.790 --> 00:01:49.777
♪ I have only one thing to do ♪

45
00:01:49.778 --> 00:01:51.890
♪ And that's be the wave
that I am. and then ♪

46
00:01:51.891 --> 00:01:54.946
♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪

47
00:01:54.947 --> 00:01:56.186
♪ I have only one thing to do ♪

48
00:01:56.187 --> 00:01:58.302
♪ And that's be the wave
that I am. and then ♪

49
00:01:58.303 --> 00:02:01.626
♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪

50
00:02:01.627 --> 00:02:02.949
♪ I have only one thing to do ♪

51
00:02:02.950 --> 00:02:05.262
♪ And that's be the wave
that I am. and then ♪

52
00:02:05.263 --> 00:02:08.660
♪ Sink back into the ocean.
sink back into the ocean ♪

53
00:02:08.661 --> 00:02:10.505
♪ Sink back into the o... ♪

54
00:02:10.506 --> 00:02:11.931
♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪

55
00:02:11.932 --> 00:02:13.750
♪ Sink back into the o... ♪

56
00:02:13.751 --> 00:02:15.376
♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪

57
00:02:15.377 --> 00:02:17.179
♪ Sink back into the ocean ♪

58
00:02:19.138 --> 00:02:27.138
<b><font color="#ff0000">Sync and corrections by btsix
www.addic7ed.com</font></b>

59
00:02:31.758 --> 00:02:35.331
- _
- [school bell ringing]

60
00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:38.750
[Petra] The early reviews
are really good.

61
00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:41.469
[Noah] So I hear. I. uh.

62
00:02:41.470 --> 00:02:43.497
I try not to pay attention
to those things.

63
00:02:44.303 --> 00:02:46.844
I have to admit. I wasn't
such a fan of Descent.

64
00:02:46.845 --> 00:02:48.928
although. clearly. the
book didn't suffer

65
00:02:48.929 --> 00:02:51.177
from lack of fans. but...

66
00:02:51.178 --> 00:02:53.135
The Autobiography of Jack Hunter.

67
00:02:53.136 --> 00:02:55.075
it really moved me.

68
00:02:55.076 --> 00:02:59.302
It's a much more vulnerable.
mature piece of writing.

69
00:02:59.303 --> 00:03:00.980
Thanks.

70
00:03:00.981 --> 00:03:04.064
I mean. I... I wrote it in prison

71
00:03:04.065 --> 00:03:06.386
partly just to. uh. keep
myself from going insane.

72
00:03:06.387 --> 00:03:08.302
So just to get it published
at all is gratifying. and...

73
00:03:08.303 --> 00:03:11.509
You were in prison for killing
your brother-in-law. right?

74
00:03:12.389 --> 00:03:15.302
Uh. my. uh. ex-wife's
brother-in-law. yeah.

75
00:03:15.989 --> 00:03:17.669
But there's plenty of stuff
out there about that.

76
00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:18.842
I-I really don't want to

77
00:03:18.843 --> 00:03:20.761
- make this about...
- No. no. no. It's just...

78
00:03:20.762 --> 00:03:22.094
ten years ago you were

79
00:03:22.095 --> 00:03:23.752
a public school teacher
living in Brooklyn.

80
00:03:23.753 --> 00:03:26.761
and then one summer. you wrote a novel

81
00:03:26.762 --> 00:03:28.427
that was an overnight sensation.

82
00:03:28.428 --> 00:03:31.761
You left your wife and family.
you married your mistress.

83
00:03:31.762 --> 00:03:34.052
you became suddenly famous and...

84
00:03:34.053 --> 00:03:35.719
I don't know. let's say you drank

85
00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:37.248
a little bit of your own Kool-Aid.

86
00:03:38.275 --> 00:03:40.260
You became increasingly arrogant.

87
00:03:40.261 --> 00:03:43.761
self-absorbed. reckless.
until one fateful night

88
00:03:43.762 --> 00:03:45.327
on the dark roads of Montauk.

89
00:03:45.328 --> 00:03:46.969
you hit someone and fled
the scene of the crime...

90
00:03:46.970 --> 00:03:48.917
I'm going somewhere with this.

91
00:03:48.918 --> 00:03:49.969
I hope so.

92
00:03:49.970 --> 00:03:53.302
You had an enormous fall from grace.

93
00:03:53.303 --> 00:03:55.508
You went to prison. you served time.

94
00:03:55.509 --> 00:03:58.133
you... lost everything.

95
00:03:59.034 --> 00:04:00.427
And now you're out.

96
00:04:00.428 --> 00:04:02.928
you've gone back to teaching
underprivileged kids.

97
00:04:02.929 --> 00:04:04.969
you have moved to be
closer to your family.

98
00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:06.966
You seem to be living a quiet life now.

99
00:04:08.415 --> 00:04:10.025
You've come full circle.

100
00:04:11.823 --> 00:04:14.552
So would you say that the redemption

101
00:04:14.553 --> 00:04:16.798
of Noah Solloway is complete?

102
00:04:18.762 --> 00:04:20.261
[chuckles softly]

103
00:04:22.613 --> 00:04:23.697
Um...

104
00:04:27.818 --> 00:04:30.387
Uh. y-you read the book. y-you tell me.

105
00:04:31.844 --> 00:04:34.010
That seems like a perfect place to stop.

106
00:04:36.220 --> 00:04:38.277
I'm really excited about this piece.

107
00:04:38.278 --> 00:04:40.590
People love a comeback story.

108
00:04:40.591 --> 00:04:41.969
When will they run it. do you know?

109
00:04:41.970 --> 00:04:44.469
Well. it's not up to me. but. um.

110
00:04:44.470 --> 00:04:46.930
they're hoping to time it with
the release of your movie.

111
00:04:46.931 --> 00:04:48.769
Your book is coming out
around then. too. isn't it?

112
00:04:48.770 --> 00:04:49.949
That's right.

113
00:04:49.950 --> 00:04:51.844
It's quite a year you're having.

114
00:04:51.845 --> 00:04:53.510
Oh. um. one more thing.

115
00:04:53.511 --> 00:04:54.785
Are you seeing anyone?

116
00:04:56.453 --> 00:04:58.527
Our readers will want to know.

117
00:05:00.484 --> 00:05:02.863
Uh... no.

118
00:05:02.864 --> 00:05:04.245
No. not at the moment.

119
00:05:04.246 --> 00:05:06.498
Really? That surprises me.

120
00:05:07.537 --> 00:05:08.844
Yeah. well. I guess that's. uh.

121
00:05:08.845 --> 00:05:10.678
that's one piece of the puzzle

122
00:05:10.679 --> 00:05:12.678
I haven't quite figured out yet.

123
00:05:13.585 --> 00:05:14.792
There's still time.

124
00:05:15.505 --> 00:05:18.179
Oh. I should probably turn this off.

125
00:05:18.845 --> 00:05:20.344
You still use those things?

126
00:05:20.345 --> 00:05:21.678
I thought young reporters these days

127
00:05:21.679 --> 00:05:22.886
just used their iPhone.

128
00:05:22.887 --> 00:05:24.427
Well. I'm not that young.

129
00:05:24.428 --> 00:05:26.672
and the batteries on these
things last longer.

130
00:05:26.673 --> 00:05:29.177
The last time I saw one.
I was interviewing

131
00:05:29.178 --> 00:05:31.135
a friend in Freshman Psych.

132
00:05:31.136 --> 00:05:33.120
Oh. you know. speaking of friends.

133
00:05:33.121 --> 00:05:34.987
could I call some of them?

134
00:05:34.988 --> 00:05:36.675
You know. to round out the picture?

135
00:05:36.676 --> 00:05:39.010
Who is Noah Solloway. the man?

136
00:05:39.011 --> 00:05:41.135
- Uh. sure. Of course.
- [door closes]

137
00:05:41.136 --> 00:05:42.678
[Joel] I can do that.

138
00:05:42.679 --> 00:05:46.594
I can... talk... for the article.

139
00:05:46.595 --> 00:05:48.094
You're Petra Ranes. I love your work.

140
00:05:48.095 --> 00:05:50.094
I-I read everything you write.

141
00:05:50.095 --> 00:05:51.969
[Petra] Oh. thanks. Uh. who are you?

142
00:05:51.970 --> 00:05:54.184
I'm the principal. actually.

143
00:05:54.185 --> 00:05:57.354
Of this. uh. school.

144
00:05:57.355 --> 00:05:58.844
But we're also friends.

145
00:05:58.845 --> 00:06:01.386
And I'm a novelist. too.
so we have that whole

146
00:06:01.387 --> 00:06:03.344
- simpatico thing going. and...
- You know what?

147
00:06:03.345 --> 00:06:04.761
I-I'll. uh. I'll think
of a couple of names

148
00:06:04.762 --> 00:06:06.094
- and get back to you.
- Great.

149
00:06:06.095 --> 00:06:07.386
Thank you for your time.

150
00:06:07.387 --> 00:06:08.665
Thank you.

151
00:06:16.787 --> 00:06:19.073
Vanity Fair?

152
00:06:19.074 --> 00:06:20.552
Wow.

153
00:06:20.553 --> 00:06:22.788
This is gonna be big for you.

154
00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:25.834
- We'll see.
- I mean. this is...

155
00:06:25.835 --> 00:06:28.302
top-tier literary recognition.

156
00:06:28.303 --> 00:06:30.094
That's rarified air.

157
00:06:30.095 --> 00:06:32.286
You want to go out? Celebrate tonight?

158
00:06:32.287 --> 00:06:34.135
Talk about our craft?

159
00:06:34.136 --> 00:06:35.594
Uh. no. I got to. um.

160
00:06:35.595 --> 00:06:37.344
I got to have dinner with my daughter.

161
00:06:37.345 --> 00:06:39.637
and then I'm gonna be on
set till-till late. so...

162
00:06:39.638 --> 00:06:41.135
"I'm gonna be on set."

163
00:06:41.136 --> 00:06:43.094
Jesus. man. Who are you?

164
00:06:43.095 --> 00:06:45.636
It's okay. I stay up
late. I'll call you.

165
00:06:45.637 --> 00:06:48.594
I mean. I got to buy a beer
for the man who has it all.

166
00:06:48.595 --> 00:06:50.219
Maybe.

167
00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:52.177
[indistinct chatter]

168
00:06:52.178 --> 00:06:54.345
[soft piano music playing]

169
00:07:01.317 --> 00:07:03.096
Is Colin coming.

170
00:07:03.097 --> 00:07:04.337
- or should we just order?
- Uh. no.

171
00:07:04.338 --> 00:07:06.344
He'll be here. He just...

172
00:07:06.345 --> 00:07:08.094
When he works. he can get carried away.

173
00:07:08.095 --> 00:07:09.876
lose track of time.

174
00:07:09.877 --> 00:07:12.380
I can't believe you're getting married.

175
00:07:12.381 --> 00:07:14.181
I know. Me either.

176
00:07:15.501 --> 00:07:16.719
You okay?

177
00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:18.255
Yeah. I'm fine.

178
00:07:19.506 --> 00:07:21.466
- How's work?
- Work's fine.

179
00:07:24.758 --> 00:07:26.029
Whit.

180
00:07:27.614 --> 00:07:29.135
Is something wrong?

181
00:07:29.136 --> 00:07:31.778
I don't want to pry.
but you seem kind of.

182
00:07:31.779 --> 00:07:33.761
- I don't know.
- I'm just tired. Dad.

183
00:07:33.762 --> 00:07:36.301
I-I have to be at the gallery
by seven every morning.

184
00:07:36.302 --> 00:07:38.552
We don't have air conditioning
'cause Andrea's too cheap.

185
00:07:38.553 --> 00:07:40.803
It's hot as hell and. you
know. I'm doing everything:

186
00:07:40.804 --> 00:07:43.719
I-I hang the art. I man the
phones. I keep the books.

187
00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:46.713
All she does is check her
Raya profile and freak out.

188
00:07:46.714 --> 00:07:48.219
What's a...? Never mind.

189
00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:49.704
So you don't like this job?

190
00:07:49.705 --> 00:07:52.052
I mean. it beats copy editing Art Forum.

191
00:07:52.053 --> 00:07:54.202
Well. maybe you could
find another gallery

192
00:07:54.203 --> 00:07:55.869
where the boss is a
little more reasonable.

193
00:07:55.870 --> 00:07:57.186
I can't quit. We need the money.

194
00:07:57.187 --> 00:07:59.813
Colin still can't work 'cause
of his visa situation. so...

195
00:07:59.814 --> 00:08:02.969
Well. would it help if
I gave you the money.

196
00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:04.844
- just to...
- Oh. no. Thanks. Dad.

197
00:08:04.845 --> 00:08:06.636
That's-that's not it. It's just that...

198
00:08:06.637 --> 00:08:08.344
like. when I come home
from a long day of work

199
00:08:08.345 --> 00:08:09.886
and I just want to. you know.

200
00:08:09.887 --> 00:08:11.511
have a glass of wine and
watch The Kardashians.

201
00:08:11.512 --> 00:08:13.929
I can't because Colin's
all over me to study.

202
00:08:13.930 --> 00:08:16.344
- Study?
- Yeah. for his immigration interview.

203
00:08:16.345 --> 00:08:18.135
You know. they put us in separate rooms.

204
00:08:18.136 --> 00:08:20.052
and if we don't get every
single question perfectly.

205
00:08:20.053 --> 00:08:21.386
Colin doesn't get his citizenship.

206
00:08:21.387 --> 00:08:23.595
Oh. hold on. hold on. Thank you.

207
00:08:25.011 --> 00:08:26.260
[chuckles]

208
00:08:26.261 --> 00:08:28.177
What?

209
00:08:29.017 --> 00:08:30.543
You remind me of your mother.

210
00:08:30.544 --> 00:08:32.094
Because I'm an alcoholic?

211
00:08:32.697 --> 00:08:33.944
No.

212
00:08:34.858 --> 00:08:36.679
'Cause you're so beautiful.

213
00:08:38.804 --> 00:08:40.170
Thanks.

214
00:08:41.379 --> 00:08:42.797
Whitney...

215
00:08:44.591 --> 00:08:47.340
this marriage thing. you don't
have to do it. you know.

216
00:08:47.928 --> 00:08:49.113
It seems rushed.

217
00:08:49.114 --> 00:08:51.511
Yeah. but actually. Dad. I
do. because if I don't.

218
00:08:51.512 --> 00:08:53.052
then Colin has to leave the country.

219
00:08:53.053 --> 00:08:54.601
Well. not forever. right?

220
00:08:54.602 --> 00:08:56.052
I mean. maybe that's for the best.

221
00:08:56.053 --> 00:08:58.052
He can go home. he can
establish himself there.

222
00:08:58.053 --> 00:08:59.923
and then apply for citizenship
on his own merit.

223
00:08:59.924 --> 00:09:02.010
What are you talking about? I'm
not gonna let him get deported.

224
00:09:02.011 --> 00:09:03.265
I-I love him.

225
00:09:03.266 --> 00:09:04.596
I just...

226
00:09:05.553 --> 00:09:07.926
I don't think it's supposed
to be this hard. Whitney.

227
00:09:08.553 --> 00:09:10.260
You are so young.

228
00:09:10.261 --> 00:09:12.358
It's too early to be this hard.

229
00:09:12.359 --> 00:09:14.344
I don't know if you
remember. Mr. Big Shot.

230
00:09:14.345 --> 00:09:16.135
but you were a struggling
artist once. too.

231
00:09:16.136 --> 00:09:17.856
Mom didn't leave you.

232
00:09:17.857 --> 00:09:20.428
I mean. you left her
20 years later. but...

233
00:09:23.704 --> 00:09:25.977
Whitney. I... I had a job.

234
00:09:26.937 --> 00:09:28.427
I was a teacher.

235
00:09:28.428 --> 00:09:30.427
I never let your mother support me.

236
00:09:30.428 --> 00:09:31.678
Look. I'm not saying

237
00:09:31.679 --> 00:09:32.886
- he's not a good guy...
- [Colin] Sorry.

238
00:09:32.887 --> 00:09:35.251
- Sorry. Mr. Solloway.
- Hi.

239
00:09:35.252 --> 00:09:38.024
- Whit. How you doing?
- Hi.

240
00:09:38.025 --> 00:09:40.101
I got a bit lost in the work. [sniffs]

241
00:09:40.848 --> 00:09:42.241
Have we ordered?

242
00:09:43.307 --> 00:09:45.094
No. Here.

243
00:09:45.095 --> 00:09:46.313
Here you go.

244
00:09:46.314 --> 00:09:47.887
Oh. thanks.

245
00:09:50.881 --> 00:09:52.421
Do they do vegan?

246
00:09:58.136 --> 00:09:59.762
[phone ringing]

247
00:10:04.387 --> 00:10:06.715
- Hi.
- [Janelle] Hi.

248
00:10:07.966 --> 00:10:09.551
Long time.

249
00:10:10.553 --> 00:10:13.804
Um... I know. At least a month. right?

250
00:10:15.268 --> 00:10:17.075
It's three. actually.

251
00:10:17.804 --> 00:10:19.550
Has it been three months? Wow.

252
00:10:19.551 --> 00:10:21.887
Time really does fly when you're busy.

253
00:10:24.621 --> 00:10:26.135
Why are you calling. Janelle?

254
00:10:26.136 --> 00:10:29.636
I feel badly about the way
things ended between us.

255
00:10:29.637 --> 00:10:31.302
You mean. when you disappeared

256
00:10:31.303 --> 00:10:33.469
after my ex-wife's boyfriend's funeral

257
00:10:33.470 --> 00:10:35.010
and then never returned my calls?

